<exercise>
<statement><p>
Calculate <m>\int_C \left(\frac{xy}{z}\right)\dee{s}</m>, where <m>C</m> is the curve <m>\left( \frac23t^3 , \sqrt{3}t^2 , 3t \right)</m> from <m>t=1</m> to <m>t=2</m>.
</p></statement>
<hint><p>
Following Definition<nbsp/><xref ref="def_lineIntegral"/>, set <m>f(x,y,z)=\frac{xy}{z}</m>, <m>x(t)=\frac23 t^3</m>, <m>y(t)=\sqrt3t^2</m>, and <m>z(t)=3t</m>.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
<m> \frac{4}{21\sqrt 3}(2^7-1) + \frac{2}{5\sqrt 3}(2^5-1)</m>
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
Following Definition<nbsp/><xref ref="def_lineIntegral"/>:
<md>
<mrow>
\int_C \left(\frac{xy}{z}\right)\dee{s}&amp;=\int_1^2 \left(\frac{\frac23t^3 \cdot \sqrt{3}t^2}{ 3t} \right)\sqrt{(2t^2)^2+(2\sqrt3 t)^2+(3)^2}\,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_1^2 \left(\frac{2}{ 3\sqrt 3} \,t^4\right)(2t^2+3)\,\dee{t} = \frac{4}{21\sqrt 3}(2^7-1) + \frac{2}{5\sqrt 3}(2^5-1)
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
	A hoop of radius <m>r</m> traces out the curve <m>x^2+y^2=1</m>, where <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are measured in metres. At a point <m>(x,y)</m>, its density is <m>x^2</m> kg per metre. What is the mass of the hoop?
</p></statement>
<hint><p>
	Parametrize the circle in the usual way.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
	<m>\pi</m> kg
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
	We parametrize the unit circle as <m>(\cos t, \sin t)</m>, <m>0 \le t \le 2\pi</m>.
</p>

<p>		A tiny slice of the hoop with length <m>\dee{s}</m> has mass <m>(x^2  \mathrm{kg}/\mathrm{m})(\dee{s}  \mathrm{m})=x^2\dee{s}  \mathrm{kg}</m>. So, the entire hoop has mass:
		<md>
<mrow>
			\int_C x^2\,\dee{s}&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi} \cos^2 t \sqrt{(-\sin t)^2+(\cos t)^2}\,\dee{t}=\int_0^{2\pi} \cos^2 t \,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\int_0^{2\pi} \frac{1+\cos(2t)}{2}\ \dee{t}
                 =\left[\frac{t}{2} +\frac{\sin(2t)}{4} \right]_0^{2\pi}=\pi  \mathrm{kg}
			</mrow>
</md>
			 For an efficient, sneaky, way to evaluate
                 <m>\int_0^{2\pi} \cos^2 t\ \dee{t}</m>, see Example
                 <xref ref="eg_workIntegralB"/>.
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
	Compute <m>\int_C (xy+z) \dee{s}</m> where <m>C</m> is the straight line from <m>(1,2,3)</m> to <m>(2,4,5)</m>.
</p></statement>
<hint><p>
	<m>C</m> can be parametrized as <m>(1+t,2+2t,3+2t)</m> for <m>0 \le t \le 1</m>.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
	<m>26</m>
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
	To parametrize <m>C</m>, we note the vector between the two points is <m>(2-1,4-2,5-3)=(1,2,2)</m>. So, the line is <m>(1,2,3)+t(1,2,2)</m> for <m>0 \le t \le 1</m>. That is, <m>x(t)=1+t</m>, <m>y(t)=2+2t</m>, and <m>z(t)=3+2t</m>.
	<md>
<mrow>
		\int_C(xy+z)\dee{s}&amp;=\int_0^1 \left((1+t)(2+2t)+(3+2t)\right)\sqrt{1^1+2^2+2^2}\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
		&amp;=              \int_0^1 3\big(5 + 6t + 2t^2\big)\ \dee{t}=26
		</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
Evaluate the path integral <m>\int_\cC f(x,y,z)\,\dee{s}</m> for
<ol label="a">
<li>
<m>f(x,y,z)=x\cos z</m>,  <m>\cC:\vr(t)=t\hi+t^2\hj</m>,
<m>0\le t\le 1</m>.
</li>
<li> <m>f(x,y,z)=\frac{x+y}{y+z}</m>,
<m>\cC:\vr(t)= \big(t,\frac{2}{3}t^{3/2},t\big)</m>,
<m>1\le t\le 2</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>\frac{5^{3/2}-1}{12}</m></p><p>
(b) <m>\frac{8-3^{3/2}}{3/2}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a)
In this case <m>\vr(t)=t\hi+t^2\hj</m>, so that
<m>\vv(t)=\diff{\vr}{t}(t)=\hi+2t\hj</m> and <m>\diff{s}{t}=\sqrt{1+4t^2} </m>. Hence
<md>
<mrow>
\int_\cC f(x,y,z)\,\dee{s}
&amp;=\int_0^1 x(t)\cos z(t) \diff{s}{t}\,\dee{t}
=\int_0^1 t(\cos 0) \sqrt{1+4t^2}\,\dee{t}
=\frac{1}{8}\frac{ {(1+4t^2)}^{3/2}}{3/2}\bigg|_0^1
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{5^{3/2}-1}{12}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<p>(b) In this case <m>\vr(t)=\big(t,\frac{2}{3}t^{3/2},t\big)</m>, so
that
<m>\vv(t)=\diff{\vr}{t}(t)=\big(1,t^{1/2},1\big)</m> and
<m>\diff{s}{t}=\sqrt{2+t} </m>. Hence
<md>
<mrow>
\int_\cC f(x,y,z)\,\dee{s}
&amp;=\int_1^2 \frac{x(t)+y(t)}{y(t)+z(t)} \, \diff{s}{t}\,\dee{t}
=\int_1^2 \frac{t+{2\over 3}t^{3/2}}{{2\over3}t^{3/2}+t} \sqrt{2+t}\,\dee{t}
=\frac{(2+t)^{3/2}}{3/2}\bigg|_1^2
</mrow><mrow>
&amp;=\frac{8-3^{3/2}}{3/2}
</mrow>
</md>
</p>

</solution>
</exercise>

<exercise>
<statement><p>
	Evaluate <m>\int_C \sin x\,\dee{s}</m>, where <m>C</m> is the curve <m>(\arcsec(t), \ln t)</m>, <m>1 \le t \le \sqrt{2}</m>.
</p></statement>
<hint><p>
	Simplify! Also: <m>\diff{}{t}\{\arcsec t\} = \frac{1}{|t|\sqrt{t^2-1}}</m>.
</p></hint>
<answer><p>
	<m>\frac12 \ln 2</m>
</p></answer>
<solution><p>
  In the figure below, we construct a triangle with <m>\theta=\arcsec t</m>; the hypotenuse has length <m>t</m>, while the side adjacent to <m>\theta</m> has length 1. By the Pythagorean Theorem, the remaining side has length <m>\sqrt{t^2-1}</m>, so <m>\sin\theta=\sin(\arcsec t)=\frac{\sqrt{t^2-1}}{t}</m>.
</p>

<sidebyside width="50%">
  <image>
<latex-image>
    \trigtri{\theta}{1}{\sqrt{t^2-1}}{t}
</latex-image>
</image>
</sidebyside>

<p>
 Remember <m>\diff{}{t}\{\ln t\} = \frac{1}{t}</m> and <m>\diff{}{t}\{\arcsec t\} = \frac{1}{|t|\sqrt{t^2-1}}</m>. In our range, <m>1 \le t \le \sqrt 2</m>, we have <m>|t|=t</m>.
	<md>
<mrow>
		\int_C \sin x \,\dee{s}&amp;=\int_{1}^{\sqrt 2}\sin\left(\arcsec t \right)\sqrt{\left(\frac{1}{t\sqrt{t^2-1}} \right)^2+\left(\frac1t \right)^2}\,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
		&amp;=\int_1^{\sqrt{2}} \frac{\sqrt{t^2-1}}{t}\sqrt{\frac{1}{t^2(t^2-1)}+\frac{1}{t^2}} \,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
		&amp;=\int_1^{\sqrt 2}\frac1t\,\dee{t}=\frac{1}{2}\ln 2
	</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>

<exercise><title><fromexam>M317 2012J</fromexam></title>
<statement><p>
A particle of mass <m>m = 1</m> has position <m>\vr(0) = \hj</m> and
velocity <m>\vv_0 = \hi + \hk</m> at time <m>t = 0</m>. The particle moves
under a force
<me>
\vF(t) = \hj - \sin t\,\hk
</me>
where <m>t</m> denotes time.
<ol label="a">
<li>
Find the position <m>\vr(t)</m> of the particle as a function of <m>t</m>.
</li>
<li>
Find the position <m>\vr(t_1)</m> of the particle when it crosses the
plane <m>x = \pi/2</m> for the first time at <m>t_1</m>.
</li>
<li>
Determine the work done by <m>\vF</m> in moving the particle from <m>\vr(0)</m> to
<m>\vr(t_1)</m>.
</li>
</ol>
</p></statement>

<hint><p>
Newton's law of motion is <m>\vF=m\va</m>. The work done over a displacement <m>\dee{\vr}</m> is <m>W=\vF \cdot \dee{\vr}</m>.
</p></hint>

<answer><p>
(a) <m>\vr(t) = t\,\hi +\Big(1+\frac{t^2}{2}\Big)\,\hj + \sin t\,\hk</m></p><p>
(b) <m>\vr(\pi/2) = \frac{\pi}{2}\,\hi  +\Big(1+\frac{\pi^2}{8}\Big)\,\hj + \hk</m>
   </p><p>
(c) <m>\frac{\pi^2}{8}-\frac{1}{2}</m>
</p></answer>

<solution><p>
(a) Since the particle has mass <m>m=1</m>, Newton's law of motion
<m>m\va=\vF</m> simplifies to
<me>
\vr''(t) = \hj - \sin t\,\hk
</me>
Integrating once gives
<me>
\vr'(t) = t\,\hj + \cos t\,\hk + \mathbf{C}
</me>
for some constant vector <m>\mathbf{C}</m>.
To satisfy the initial condition that <m>\vr'(0) = \vv_0=\hi+\hk</m>,
we need
<md>
<mrow>
\hi+\hk = \vr'(0) = \hk + \mathbf{C}
\implies \mathbf{C} = \hi
</mrow>
</md>
So
<me>
\vr'(t)
        = \hi + t\,\hj + \cos t\,\hk
</me>
Integrating a second time, and imposing the initial condition that <m>\vr(0)
=\hj</m>, gives
<me>
\vr(t)  = t\,\hi + \frac{t^2}{2}\,\hj + \sin t\,\hk +\hj
        = t\,\hi +\Big(1+\frac{t^2}{2}\Big)\,\hj + \sin t\,\hk
</me>
</p>

<p>(b) The particle has <m>x(t) =\pi/2</m> when <m>t=\pi/2</m>. So
<me>
\vr(\pi/2) = \frac{\pi}{2}\,\hi  +\Big(1+\frac{\pi^2}{8}\Big)\,\hj + \hk
</me>
</p>

<p>(c) The work done is
<md>
<mrow>
\text{Work} &amp;= \int_0^{\pi/2} \vF(t)\cdot\vr'(t)\ \dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= \int_0^{\pi/2} \big(\hj - \sin t\,\hk\big)\cdot
         \big(\hi + t\,\hj + \cos t\,\hk\big)\ \dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= \int_0^{\pi/2} \big(t-\sin t\cos t\big)\,\dee{t}
</mrow><mrow>
  &amp;= \Big[\frac{t^2}{2} +\frac{1}{2}\cos^2 t\Big]_0^{\pi/2}
</mrow><mrow>
  &amp; = \frac{\pi^2}{8}-\frac{1}{2}
</mrow>
</md>
</p></solution>
</exercise>
